## Observations (Claude, 2026-06-10)

Reviewed against the three PDFs in this folder (Proposal Blair 2025-08-20, Invoice S9927_Final, Get Energy June 2026 Bill) and the linked Google Sheet.

### The numbers that define the investment

- **System:** 9.0 kW DC, 18 LONGi 500W panels + 9 APS DS3 microinverters. Estimated Year 1 production 11,391 kWh; 25-yr production 258,899 kWh (0.5%/yr degradation). *(Proposal pp. 2, 8)*
- **Price:** $22,050 + GST. Final invoice was $16,537.50 + $826.88 GST = $17,364.38, implying a ~$5,512.50 deposit was paid earlier. Total cash cost ≈ **$23,152.50** including GST, plus the **$300** assessment fee. *(Invoice S9927; Proposal p. 5)*
- **Loan:** $183.75/mo × 120 = **$22,050 exactly** — interest-free, matching the pre-GST system price. GST (~$1,102) and the $300 fee were effectively out-of-pocket extras the loan didn't cover.

### What the linked spreadsheet actually models

The note describes it as tracking *daily power generation*, but the shared tab is an **annual savings model**, not generation data (no daily figures were accessible). Its logic:

| Component | Annual |
|---|---|
| Current cost estimate | $2,429 |
| New electricity annual cost | $875 |
| **Enmax savings (difference)** | **$1,554** |
| Solar Club | $600 |
| Carbon Offset | $300 |
| **Total annual savings** | **$2,454** |
| Annual loan payment | $2,205 |
| **Net while loan is active** | **+$249/yr** |

So the model says you net roughly **+$249/year** even while paying the loan, then capture the **full ~$2,454/year** once the loan is retired (year 11+).

**Flag — internal inconsistency in the sheet:** the "Monthly Energy Savings" row sums to **$1,335/yr**, but the model's total uses the **$1,554** Enmax figure instead. These two estimates of electricity savings don't reconcile (a ~$219 gap). The $1,335 row looks like an older/separate estimate that isn't wired into the total. Worth deciding which one you trust.

### Real-world performance (first bill in folder beats the model)

The Get Energy bill for **Apr 21 – May 19, 2026** is the strongest evidence so far:

- Solar exported **743 kWh** to the grid; only 436 kWh imported.
- Microgen credit earned: **−$260.05** (743 kWh @ $0.35/kWh).
- Net electricity charge: **−$41.90 — a credit**, which was even transferred over to offset the natural gas bill. *(Bill pp. 5–6)*

For a single ~4-week spring period, the microgen credit alone ($260) was roughly **double** the model's April/May monthly savings ($110/$125). The electricity side of the bill is currently running at zero/credit. **Caveat:** this is peak-season production, and the **$0.35/kWh fixed rate is locked only Apr 2026–Apr 2027** — both export credits and savings will shift when that rate resets. Winter months (Nov–Feb in the model: $70–$85) will pull the average down.

### Payback / ROI

- Simple payback on full cash cost (~$23,450) at $2,454/yr ≈ **9.5 years** — and it lands close to when the interest-free loan is paid off, so the system is roughly **self-funding** over the 10-year loan term.
- Flat 25-yr net ≈ 25 × $2,454 − $23,450 ≈ **~$37,900**. The proposal's headline **$44,734 over 25 years** is higher because it assumes **5.7%/yr electricity inflation** (escalating savings), which the flat spreadsheet does not. *(Proposal pp. 6, 8)*

### Suggested next steps

1. Pick which electricity-savings figure ($1,335 vs $1,554) is real and fix the sheet so the total ties out.
2. Confirm the **Solar Club ($600)** and **Carbon Offset ($300)** credits are actually active on your account — together they're 37% of modeled savings, and the bill shows "Solar Club" messaging but I couldn't confirm the dollar credits are flowing.
3. Add a tab tracking **actual monthly microgen credits** vs. the model — one more billing cycle and you'll have real data to replace the estimates.
4. Watch the **Apr 2027 rate reset** — it directly drives both savings and export credits.

